# Pull request style

Write PRs the way CTNicholas does: short, plain, and information-dense. Default
to less. A reviewer should understand the change in a few seconds.

## Titles

- Write the title as a short, high-level sentence in present tense, ending with
  a period. It usually reads like a trimmed version of the description's summary
  line.
  - e.g. `Adds Superdoc example and get started guide.`
- Use present-tense `-s` verbs: `Adds`, `Updates`, `Fixes`, `Removes`,
  `Improves` — not the imperative (`Add`, `Update`, `Fix`).
- Stay high-level. Omit internal package/folder names and framework qualifiers
  unless essential. Prefer `Superdoc example` over `nextjs-yjs-superdoc
  example`, and drop redundant words like "React".
- Sentence case (not Title Case). Proper names keep their casing (e.g. `AI`,
  `CHANGELOG`).
- Write "get started" with a space, not "get-started".
- Optionally prefix with a scope and a colon when it helps, especially for
  examples: `Example:` for one, `Examples:` for several.

Worked example for titles:

- Too detailed (avoid):
  `Add nextjs-yjs-superdoc example and SuperDoc React get-started guide`
- Target (do this): `Adds Superdoc example and get started guide.`

## Descriptions

Aim very low on length. Most PRs are a one-line summary plus a few short
bullets. Describe the change at a high level, from the reader's/user's point of
view — what was added or what it does — not how it's wired internally.

- Lead with one short summary sentence. Link the product/feature name when there
  is one. Don't enumerate the tech stack or list every sub-change.
  - e.g. `Adds a [Superdoc](https://www.superdoc.dev/) example and matching get started guide.`
- Then a short bullet list, one bullet per notable item. In each bullet,
  backtick the **short identifying name** (the example folder name or a file's
  base name), then `: ` and a brief, **capitalized, period-terminated** sentence
  describing what it is or does.
  - Use the base name, NOT the full path: `` `nextjs-yjs-superdoc` `` and
    `` `yjs-superdoc-react.mdx` ``, not `examples/nextjs-yjs-superdoc` or
    `docs/pages/get-started/yjs-superdoc-react.mdx`.
  - e.g. `` - `nextjs-yjs-superdoc`: Basic example with live cursors in the text editor. ``
  - e.g. `` - `yjs-superdoc-react.mdx`: Get started guide for Superdoc. ``
- Do NOT include implementation/wiring details (which APIs are called, how
  modules/props are passed, client-import timing, type casts, etc.) unless a
  reviewer genuinely needs them.
- Do NOT include build/test/CI status or "how to test" notes unless they're
  genuinely important.
- Do NOT use PR-template-style headings such as `## Description`,
  `## Implementation notes`, or `## How to test it`.
- Reference related PRs and issues as bare URLs on their own lines.
- For visual or UI changes, include evidence: screenshots via `<img ...>` and
  videos via `<video>` / attachment URLs.
- Tuck long supplementary content (prompts, large code samples, examples) inside
  `<details><summary>…</summary> … </details>`.
- Track follow-up work with bold `**TODO**` / `**TODO AFTER**` sections using
  checkbox lists (`- [ ]` / `- [x]`).
- Plain tone. No emoji. No marketing language. No "this PR…" preamble when a
  direct statement works.
- Match the maintainer's casual product casing when they have one (e.g.
  `Superdoc`); don't fuss over official brand casing.

### Worked example

For a PR adding a SuperDoc example plus its guide, this is too verbose (avoid):

> ## Description
>
> Adds a new collaborative DOCX editor example, `examples/nextjs-yjs-superdoc`,
> built with Liveblocks, Yjs, SuperDoc, and Next.js. It follows the same
> structure as the other `nextjs-yjs-*` examples …
>
> ### Implementation notes
> - `CollaborativeEditor` gets the shared Yjs doc/provider via
>   `getYjsProviderForRoom(room)` and passes them to SuperDoc through
>   `modules.collaboration` …
>
> ### How to test it
> - `npm run build` passes …

This is the target (do this):

> Adds a [Superdoc](https://www.superdoc.dev/) example and matching get started
> guide.
>
> - `nextjs-yjs-superdoc`: Basic example with live cursors in the text editor.
> - `yjs-superdoc-react.mdx`: Get started guide for Superdoc.

## Anti-patterns (avoid)

- Long, sectioned write-ups with multiple `##` headings.
- Implementation/wiring details and tech-stack enumeration.
- Restating the diff line by line.
- Build/CI status, "How to test", or "Risks" sections unless genuinely useful.
- Full file paths where a base name is clearer.
- Title Case titles, or imperative verbs (`Add`, `Fix`) where the present-tense
  `Adds`/`Fixes` reads better.
